{"cursor":"7188","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn geometry, the 'foci' (; singular 'focus') are a pair of special points with\nreference to which any of a variety of curves is constructed. For example, foci\ncan be used in defining conic sections, the four types of which are the circle,\nellipse, parabola, and hyperbola. In addition, foci are used to define the\nCassini oval and the Cartesian oval.\n","linknr":143,"url":"Focus_(geometry)","recorded":1362667596,"links":30,"instances":["astronomy","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Conic sections","Geometric centers"],"headings":["Conics in geometry","Cartesian and Cassini ovals","Generalization","Confocal curves","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Excentricidad.svg/220px-Excentricidad.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/e/b/6eb791250af75754a4dc1894d340d3e7.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["locus","mathematics"],["barycentric_coordinates","astronomy"]],"members":["barycentric_coordinates","locus"],"related":["Geometry","Conic_section","Circle","Ellipse","Parabola","Hyperbola","Cassini_oval","Cartesian_oval","Locus_(mathematics)","Circles_of_Apollonius","Point_at_infinity","Line_at_infinity","Projective_geometry","Gravitation","Two-body_problem","Center_of_mass","Barycentric_coordinates_(astronomy)","Cartesian_oval","Weighted_sum","Cassini_oval","Circular_points_at_infinity","AF+BG_theorem"]}